# 1. Convergence test
To do the convergence test, you need to create the file template for the crystal that you want to simulate, template.{atom_name}.in inside the template folder
e.g
'''
&CONTROL
  calculation = 'scf'
  restart_mode = 'from_scratch'
  outdir = './tmp'
  pseudo_dir = './PSEUDO'
  prefix = '${atoms}'
  tstress = .true.
  tprnfor = .true.
/
&SYSTEM
  ibrav = 4
  celldm(1) = 5.82603759
  celldm(3) = 1.14206941291
  nat = 3
  ntyp = 2
  ecutwfc = $ECUT
  occupations = 'smearing', smearing='gauss', degauss=0.04,
/
&ELECTRONS
  conv_thr = 1.0e-6
/
ATOMIC_SPECIES
  Mg  24.305  Mg_ONCV_PBE_sr.upf
  B   10.811  B_ONCV_PBE_sr.upf
ATOMIC_POSITIONS crystal
  Mg   0.0000000000  0.0000000000  0.0000000000
  B    0.3333333333  0.6666666666  0.5000000000
  B    0.6666666666  0.3333333333  0.5000000000
K_POINTS automatic
  ${ks} ${ks} ${ks} 0 0 0
'''

After that, you can use the provided bash script convergence_test_on_Ecut.sh and convergence_test_on_kmesh.sh to do the convergence test. 
Command: 
./convergence_test_on_Ecut.sh 'type_your_atom_name in here' 'type_your_predicted_kmesh_in_here'
./convergence_test_on_kmesh.sh 'type_your_atom_name in here' 'type_your_predicted_Ecut_that_you_found_in_the_first_convergence_test'

Note that, you should edit convergence threshold inside the template/template.plot_deltaE.py, eg. if you need to get 10meV/atom and you have 3 atom inside your primitive cell. You got threshold=10*3 = 30 meV

